ATSI Employment in Victoria

Author

Strategy and Priority Project - Data and Analytics

Published

June 1, 2023

Abstract
The following data estimates Aboriginal and Torres Straight Islander (ATSI) unemployment rates for Victorian regions as of April 2023. This data reflects 2021 census employment levels for ATSI peoples, adjusted for fluctuations in regional employment levels that have occurred since August 2021. As the Bureau of Statistics does not report regional statistics for ATSI people at a regional level over time, any changes in employment since August 2021 only reflect the broader region’s employment trend, not improvement or deterioration in employment outcomes specific to ATSI people.

Headline employment statistics

The following charts show estimate Victoria-wide ATSI employment statistics and compare them with broader population values. Please note, census-based employment statistics will not reconcile with official labour statistics. For more information please read the data quality statement.

Maping employment

The following provides unemployment rates, participation rates and estimate working-age population of ATSI peoples by region. Regions are defined using the Australian Bureau of Statistics Statistical Area level 3. Please note that due to sample size issues, some regions may report an unemployment rate of zero. These observations likely represent statistical anomalies rather than underlying conditions.

Data quality statement

The information contained in this report attempts to bridge two knowledge gaps; ATSI employment rates since census and fine geographical disaggregation of ATSI employment. These new features may introduce the following errors:

  • Small regions with few ATSI people may report anomalous results
    For example, if a given region has few ATSI people but they are all employed, the region would report an unemployment rate of zero. Though technically correct for the snapshot of the region during census, this result does not represent the underlying conditions or likelihood of employment for ATSI people living here.

  • Movements in employment since Census don’t capture ATSI-specific changes
    While census provides a reasonably accurate picture of ATSI employment conditions, the Australian Bureau of Statistics time series employment publication does not provide any detailed ATSI information. This means that if ATSI employment conditions improved or deteriorated at a different rate to the general public, this report will not reflect the additional changes.

  • Census employment rates do not reconcile with official employment statistics
    As noted by the Australian Bureau of Statistics, Census-based employment statistics will not reconcile with Victoria’s official employment statistics. This is not to say Census statistics are inferior; it simply has a different sampling methodology.

Considering the above points, the data contained within this report should be used for indicative purposes only. No claim is made as to the accuracy or currency of any of the content in this report at any time. The Victorian Government and this agency (the Department of Jobs, Skills, Industry and Regions) do not accept any liability to any person for the information (or the use of such information) which is provided in this report, including information sourced or derived from third parties or incorporated into the repot by reference.
